129
00:19:23,555 --> 00:19:30,140
As you know, students in Massachusetts are required to take the MCAS test and they can take it in three ways.

130
00:19:30,280 --> 00:19:40,049
So the routine standard MCAS test, also the standard MCAS test with accommodations or the MCAS alternative assessment.

131
00:19:41,034 --> 00:19:53,347
Students with disabilities take the standard computer-based or paper and pencil MCAS test, either with or without accommodations, at the grade level specified for assessment in that subject.

132
00:19:54,228 --> 00:20:01,656
But there are a small number of students with disabilities, with significant disabilities, who are unable to take the standard MCAS.

133
00:20:02,357 --> 00:20:06,084
Those are our students who take the alternate assessment.

134
00:20:06,866 --> 00:20:13,077
And this is about 1% statewide of all students with the most significant disabilities that take the assessment.

135
00:20:14,112 --> 00:20:19,514
Medford Public Schools had 17 students participate this year in the alternate assessment.

136
00:20:20,514 --> 00:20:27,016
And they all consist of a portfolio of specific materials that's collected throughout the school year.

137
00:20:27,536 --> 00:20:39,140
And when I say the school year, it's typically September to March, and then the portfolio is sent into the, to DESE, where they score it and then send the results back late in the summer.

138
00:20:40,836 --> 00:20:50,368
For each student that is on an IEP or a 504, their team decides how, not whether they'll participate in the MCAS assessment.

139
00:20:51,189 --> 00:20:57,697
The teams make the determination using the guidelines found in the principal's manual for the MCAS alternative.

140
00:20:58,398 --> 00:21:01,961
And our special education teams follow this decision-making tool.

141
00:21:02,822 --> 00:21:20,016
I've included it in your packet and it's just a flow chart that they go through at every team meeting to indicate or to decide which student will be participating in the standard MCAS and which students will be participating in the alternative.

142
00:21:20,596 --> 00:21:27,242
And then they have to make that decision for each content area that the student will be taking the MCAS testing in.

143
00:21:29,729 --> 00:21:36,473
So part of the process is we have our teachers go to the training through DESE in the fall.

144
00:21:37,133 --> 00:21:49,001
There are sessions throughout the school year that the teachers can go on to get further training or to have their students portfolios looked at and get feedback from DESE representatives.

145
00:21:49,981 --> 00:22:01,445
So once we identify the students going through the decision-making flowchart, each teacher will provide the student with a skill survey for each strand.

146
00:22:01,985 --> 00:22:07,307
